1. Caching – Temporary Data Storage for Faster Retrieval

What is Caching?
Caching is a technique where frequently accessed or expensive-to-compute data is stored temporarily in a fast storage layer (cache) so that future requests can be served faster without repeatedly hitting the primary data source (database, API, filesystem).
Why Caching is Important
	• Performance improvement – Reduces response time from milliseconds/seconds to microseconds
	• Reduced database load – Fewer DB queries
	• Scalability – Helps systems handle higher traffic
	• Cost optimization – Less compute and I/O usage
Typical Cache Flow
	1. Client sends request
	2. Application checks cache
	3. If data exists → return from cache (cache hit)
	4. If not → fetch from DB, store in cache, return (cache miss)

Client → Application → Cache → Database
                  ↳ (if miss) ↳ store result

2. Caching Strategies
Caching strategies define how data is read from and written to the cache.

2.1 Write-Through Cache
Definition
In write-through caching, data is written to both cache and database synchronously.

Flow
Write Request
 → Cache
 → Database
Characteristics
	• Cache is always consistent with DB
	• Slower writes (two operations)
	• Simpler recovery

Pros
✔ Strong consistency
✔ No stale data
✔ Easy to implement

Cons
✖ Higher write latency
✖ Cache write even if data is rarely read
Best Use Case
	• Financial data
	• User profiles
	• Configuration data

2.2 Write-Back (Write-Behind) Cache
Definition
In write-back caching, data is written to the cache first, and the database update happens asynchronously later.

Flow
Write Request
 → Cache
 → (Async) Database

Characteristics
	• Faster writes
	• Risk of data loss if cache crashes

Pros
✔ Very fast write operations
✔ Reduced DB load

Cons
✖ Risk of data loss
✖ Complex failure handling
Best Use Case
	• High-write systems
	• Analytics
	• Event counters

2.3 Read-Through Cache
Definition
In read-through caching, the application always reads from the cache.
If data is missing, the cache itself loads data from DB.

Flow
Read Request
 → Cache
   → (if miss) Load from DB

Characteristics
	• Application logic remains simple
	• Cache acts as data loader

Pros
✔ Cleaner application code
✔ Automatic cache population

Cons
✖ Cache layer becomes more complex
Best Use Case
	• Centralized caching logic
	• Shared cache libraries

2.4 Cache-Aside (Lazy Loading)
Definition
In cache-aside, the application is fully responsible for reading and writing cache.

Flow
Read:
 → Cache
 → (miss) DB → Cache → Response

Write:
 → DB
 → Cache (update or evict)

Characteristics
	• Most commonly used strategy
	• Explicit control

Pros
✔ Flexible
✔ Easy to debug
✔ Works well with Spring Boot annotations

Cons
✖ Risk of stale data
✖ Requires careful eviction
Best Use Case
	• REST APIs
	• Microservices
	• Spring Boot applications

3. Distributed Caching
What is Distributed Caching?
Distributed caching is a caching approach where multiple application instances share the same cache, typically running on a separate cluster.
Instead of:
App Instance → Local Cache
We have:
Multiple Apps → Shared Cache Cluster

Why Distributed Cache?
	• Microservices architecture
	• Horizontal scaling
	• Stateless applications
	• Consistent cached data across nodes

Common Distributed Cache Technologies
	• Redis
	• Memcached
	• Hazelcast
	• AWS ElastiCache

Distributed Cache Architecture
Client
 ↓
Load Balancer
 ↓
App Instance 1 ─┐
App Instance 2 ─┼──► Distributed Cache (Redis)
App Instance 3 ─┘
                   ↓
                Database


Advantages
✔ Cache consistency across nodes
✔ High availability
✔ Better scalability
Challenges
✖ Network latency
✖ Cache eviction coordination
✖ Serialization overhead

